portion of my own education. &#10;Something that troubles me about homeschooling is that you see problems and instead of addressing them you essentially opt out of a problematic system. But the system is still problematic, probably more so because parents who are aware of how it's problematic opt out of it. Now I went to an elite private school, ultimately, so I did this myself. &#10;But homeschooling, additionally, has some societal implications beyond those posed by private schools. Specifically, if parents are qualified, rational, and essentially functional within society, homeschooling can be a great thing. But a lot of people who homeschool do so because they don't want to participate in the social structure of our society. A lot are unqualified. And since raising children is partially about doing what you want and partially about raising citizens, this is problematic. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1178" language="en" documentId="495" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="stellaluna4" date="09/05/2013" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a44369503/home_schooling_debate_this_hypothetical?cpg=11" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="495" notes="" title="Home schooling: Debate this hypothetical"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="94"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="95" end="127"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="128" end="328"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="329" end="677"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="678" end="1178"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55"/></xmi:XMI>